{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491321"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:42:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:42:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"912"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/912"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.66,0.04,0.05,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"912"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43854"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/912"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"912"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28851"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2202"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11314"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20232"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43854"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents with a one-month history of a painless swelling on the right side of her neck. She has a 20 pack-year smoking history and drinks alcohol rarely. On examination there is a firm subcutaneous swelling in the right supraclavicular fossa. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. Fine needle aspiration cytology of the neck lump confirms carcinoma in a lymph node.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Core needle biopsy","CT Chest","Bronchoscopy","Mammography","Gastroscopy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETo answer this question, it is important to know that the right supraclavicular nodes drain the breast, lung and upper oesophagus. This is not to be confused with the left supraclavicular nodes including Virchow\u0027s node, which has more extensive drainage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT Chest \u003C/strong\u003Eis the most appropriate initial step. This would be with contrast to assist with soft tissue differentiation which is better seen on CT compared to CXR. \u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E may be appropriate if there is a centrally located mass that needs to be biopsied however a CT Chest would be the most appropriate first investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to remember that head and neck cancers are a common cause of cervical node enlargement - particularly in the smoking population. Although not an option listed in this scenario, CT head and neck is commonly required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECore needle biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E (CNB) is not required as fine needle aspiration (FNA) has confirmed carcinoma. FNA is the preferred biopsy method for enlarged lymph nodes, while CNB is typically used in the investigation of a breast mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBreast cancer typically spreads first to the axillary nodes, so \u003Cstrong\u003Emammography\u003C/strong\u003E is not the answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastroscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate at this stage, given the drainage of the stomach is to the left supraclavicular nodes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Malignancy must always be considered in older patients presenting with a painless swelling in the neck."],"references":["Nasim F, Sabath BF, Wapen GA. Lung cancer. Med Clin North Am. 2019 May; 103:463-73.","Tan E, Jaya J. An Approach to Neck Mases in Adults. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2020; 49 (5). Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/may/an-approach-to-neck-masses-in-adults#:~:text=CT%20of%20the%20neck%20with,enhanced%20CT%20of%20the%20neck."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28851"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"912"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28851"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-29T13:52:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T16:35:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"912"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43854"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[]